textMap.PRIMARY: Bonus Content: This episode of "The Man In the High Castle" is one of a number of titles that benefit from exclusive videos and behind-the-scenes photos, accessible in the X-Ray Bonus tab in Prime Video.

In "The Man in the High Castle," the Japanese Imperial Army's General Hideki Tojo can be credited with the formation of the Kempeitai - the Japanese secret military police force and intelligence agency.

The production design for the Smiths' new apartment was a welcome challenge for Production Designer Drew Boughton and his team. They designed the space to incorporate a lot of glass and subtle Nazi iconography built-into the furnishings, and they also crafted a type of door that was distinctive to Berlin in the late 1950's and would not have been commonplace in a New York City apartment in 1962 in our timeline.

For two years after Japanese and Nazi powers seized control of the United States, the Rebel American Army continued to fight occupation, according to alt-history. In 1947, the remaining militants were forced into the Rocky Mountains where the rebellion was finally crushed.

In "The Man in the High Castle," The Reich controls, Europe, Africa and the middle east so their control of mineral and oil resources is far more vast than that of the Japanese Empire, which controls India, Indonesia, Australia and a large part of China. They share North America.

In Philip K. Dick's novel, Army Field Marshall Rommel becomes Reichsmarshall of America after the 1945 invasion. Rommel is primarily concerned with suppressing the Rebel American Army, which resulted in a negligent implementation of Hitler's Final Solution (complete extermination of the Jewish population). As a result, many Jewish and African Americans escaped to the Neutral Zone and the JPS during the last two years of the war.

The American Reichsmark is the favored form of currency in the Neutral Zone, but it is essentially a black-market economy, which means people will accept any valid currency (including Yen or German Marks) and barter goods of value.
"Reprisals" in the Japanese Pacific States are standard policy; civilians are rounded up and executed publicly in retaliation for at-large violations of the law.

In "The Man in the High Castle," though Japan's Army is massive, many of its high-ranking officers in the JPS were killed when the resistance detonated a bomb in Season 2; as a result, Kido finds himself reporting to Navy authority as opposed to Army leadership - a reality that deeply rankles the Army veteran.
In "The Man in the High Castle" travel can only occur when a person is in a meditative state.

In the alt-history of the TV series, J. Edgar Hoover has become head of the SD (the SS intelligence agency) in the American Reich. In our timeline, Hoover was the first director of the Bureau of Investigation, which later became the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI); he presided over the agency for 37 years.

In "The Man in the High Castle," Army and Navy are divided along ideological lines. This matches real-world history, in which the Navy's Admiral Yamamoto was considered to be philosophical and intellectual, while the Army's General Tojo was ambitious, Machiavellian, and a hardline militarist.

Throughout the Greater Nazi Reich, Jewish and African American music, art, literature, and achievement is banned and has been erased from accessible public record. Blues, Soul, Rock and Roll, Boogie-woogie, and Jazz do not exist in Nazi-dominated states but these art forms have gained a slight foothold in the Neutral Zone and the Pacific States.
